          <title level="a" type="main">Sadder than Simonidean Tears: Cornificius and Simonides in Catullus 38. Avec résumé en anglais.</title>
          <author n="1">
            <surname>KOWERSKI</surname>
            <forename>Lawrence M.</forename>
          </author>
          <series>
            <title level="j" type="main">Classical Weekly, puis Classical World</title>
            <title level="j" type="short">CW</title>
            <biblScope type="issue">101</biblScope>
          </series>
          <date>2007-2008</date>
          <biblScope type="page" from="139" to="157"/>
          <note type="annotation">Catullus' poem 38 is not a request for consolatory verses from Cornificius in the vein of Simonides, but for some verses from his epyllion, the Glaucus. The so-called &amp;quot;new Simonides&amp;quot; [P. Oxy. XXII, 2327 [= M.-P.3 1459.1; LDAB 3915); LIX, 3965 (= M.-P.3 1459.11; LDAB 3919)] reveals Simonides' appropriateness as a model for epic-like verses.</note>
        </bibl>
